<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="422" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,477,1332]" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,981,1008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Comments.</emphasis>
The general appearance and structure of the 
<typeStatus box="[833,881,982,1008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">type</typeStatus>
species of this genus is remarkably similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moulton" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[181,445,1017,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Kladothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennatus">
<emphasis box="[181,445,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Kladothrips antennatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its close relatives all of which live in pouch galls on the phyllodes of 
<taxonomicName box="[1271,1349,1018,1044]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1271,1349,1018,1044]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Crespi, B. J. &amp; Morris, D. C. &amp; Mound, L. A." box="[159,365,1053,1080]" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" refId="ref3323" refString="Crespi, B. J., Morris, D. C. &amp; Mound, L. A. (2004) Evolution of ecological and behavioural diversity: Australian Acacia thrips as model organisms. Australian Biological Resources Study &amp; Australian National Insect Collection, CSIRO, Canberra, 328 pp." type="book" year="2004">
Crespi 
<emphasis box="[241,290,1053,1079]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
). However, macropterae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Froggatt" authorityYear="1906" box="[675,809,1053,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Kladothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[675,809,1053,1079]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Kladothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have duplicated cilia on the posterior margin of the fore wing, and also have only two sub-basal wing setae. Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Froggatt" authorityYear="1906" box="[937,1071,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Kladothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[937,1071,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Kladothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species the postocular setae are usually short, and no member of that genus has two pairs of these setae. Similarly, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Froggatt" authorityYear="1906" box="[1082,1216,1125,1151]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Kladothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1082,1216,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Kladothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species rarely have the pronotal anteromarginal setae longer than the discal setae, and on the abdomen the pelta is slightly longer than wide, and the tube shorter than the head. As indicated above, the structural similarities between this new species and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moulton" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[151,306,1234,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Kladothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennatus">
<emphasis box="[151,306,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">K. antennatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be correlated in some way with life in a tightly closed gall, rather than an indication of phylogenetic relationship. This gall on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Merr" authorityYear="1951" baseAuthorityName="Brongn. &amp; Gris" box="[498,729,1269,1295]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Putranjivaceae" genus="Drypetes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deplanchei">
<emphasis box="[498,729,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Drypetes deplanchei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very different (
<figureCitation box="[928,992,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1637,1662]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,179,1609]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,179,1609]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Drypetothrips korykis gen et sp. n. and galls. (1) Drypetes deplanchei leaf margin galls; (2) holotype head and pronotum; (3) meso and metanotum; (4) antenna; (5) prosternites; (6) tergite IX and tube; (7) pelta and tergites II–IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741290/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) from the more open leaf-roll galls that are induced by several 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1919" box="[409,554,1305,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Teuchothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[409,554,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Teuchothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in 
<collectingCountry box="[677,783,1305,1331]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="422">Australia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
